node.text:
Karla Zazueta @mexicanfoodmemories shows us her fathers favourite breakfast, Bistec Rancheros. 
I started to write and blog about Mexican food, not only because I wanted to show people in UK that you can cook authentic and delicious Mexican food with the ingredients you find in UK, but also because I wanted to teach my children the richness about our cuisine and to preserve my family recipes.

So one thing led to another one and now my blog adventure led me to start teaching people how to cook Mexican food in London. I also do supper clubs from time to time and cook for small dinner parties.

I decided to cook this for you, because although we have lots of famous Mexican breakfasts, like chilaquiles or huevos rancheros, this breakfast is super special for me, as it used to be my dad’s favourite breakfast.

I’m from the north of Mexico, from Baja California and we love our carnes asadas (barbecues) so we eat a lot of meat, arrachera (bavette) is our favourite. So this breakfast is simple, but packed with Northern Mexican flavours. It is always serve with refried beans, fresh made corn tortillas, spicy salsa and eggs. My dad used to have black coffee and orange juice to drink with it.

Serves 2
Ingredients
300 gr bavette steak or any steak cut thinly strips
2 tomatoes
1/2 onion
1/2 green pepper
1 large fresh jalapeño
Salt to taste
Pinch of ground black pepper
2 tbsp rapeseed or vegetable oil
To serve
Refried beans
Fried eggs
Corn tortillas
Spicy salsa
Method
Start by making the salsa and tortillas.
Chop all the vegetables in julienned and have them ready. Heat a frying pan then add the oil.
Once the oil is hot, add the vegetables, fry for 5 min, mixing continuously and add all the steak. Add salt and ground black pepper.
While the meat is frying, cook the beans and fry the eggs.
Cook the bistec for 7 min. Do not over cook it, otherwise it will be very chewy.
To serve, spread some refried beans onto a plate then put some bistec ranchero and the eggs. Eat it with corn tortillas, spicy salsa. Enjoy

Mapo Doufu with CHEESE! Move over shakshuka. A true icon of Chinese cooking is welcomed into the world of breakfast/brunch. Leave the pork out for a vegan recipe and give it a go at the weekend #symmetrybreakfast
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
1 tbsp fermented black beans, mashed
2 tbsp chilli oil or chilli paste
- You can use doubanjiang, which is often both combined, but I prefer separate so I can control saltiness and spiciness 
2 cloves garlic, minced/grated
2 tsp Sichuan peppercorns
50g piece of belly pork, minced
3 red chillis, finely chopped
2 tbsp light soy sauce
2 tbsp black Chinese vinegar
2 tbsp rice wine
240ml (1 cup) vegetable stock
400g soft firm tofu (not silken tofu!)
1 tsp of grape seed or vegetable oil 
Drizzle of sesame oil for garnish
Pinch of sugar 
1 tsp cornflower
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
1 - Pick out the hard stone from the peppercorn if any and discard, toast the peppercorn in a dry frying pan until fragrant. Leave to cool and crush into a powder
2 - In a cold wok, add the grapeseed oil and pork belly and cook on medium low for 15 minutes.
3 - Add the fermented black beans, cook for 5 minutes, then add the garlic and sugar
4 - Add the chilli oil or paste and fresh chilli and cook for a further 5 minutes 
5 - Add the soy sauce, vinegar and rice wine.
6 - Add the vegetable stock and cook for a further 10 minutes 
7 - Mix the cornflour with a dash of cold water to make a paste, add this to your sauce. Bring it up to a gentle boil for 5 minutes to thicken
8 - Add the ground Sichuan peppercorn and stir through 
9 - Prepare a pan with boiling salted water
10 - Cut the tofu into cubes, roughly 1 inch/2cm cubes
11 - Gently add the tofu to the boiling water, try not to touch it and after 4-5 minutes, remove the tofu and drop into the sauce.
12 - Simmer for a further 5-10 minutes and serve over white rice or cover it in CHEESE and stick it under a grill/broiler

TOPPING
60g soft butter
40g sugar
1 egg
80g plain flour
20g cornflour
25g milk powder
Pinch of salt

BUNS
300g Plain flour
25g Milk powder
50g sugar
1 egg,
7g fast action yeast
140ml water, room temperature
Pinch salt

Plus one egg for glazing at the end

METHOD

Topping first
1 – Cream together the butter and sugar on a medium speed for 5 minutes
2 – Add the egg and continue until pale
3 – Combine the rest of the ingredients together and add to the butter mix one tablespoon at a time
4 – Once thoroughly combined, scrape into a clean bowl and chill in the fridge. 
This stage can be done in advance and needs at least 2 hours to chill

Then the BUNS
1 – In a stand mixer with a hook attachment, add the flour, milk powder, sugar, yeast and salt.
2 – Add the water and egg and on a low speed, combine it all until the dough comes away from the sides of the bowl. If its too dry, add a teaspoon of water, too wet, add a teaspoon of flour.
3 – Remove the dough from the mixer and shape into a ball. Place in a new clean bowl and cover with a cloth. Leave to rise in a warm place for 1 hour.
4 – Remove the dough and give it a knead, knocking out some of the air
5 – Weigh the dough and cut into 6 even pieces making them all roughly the same weight. Shape each piece into smooth balls and cover again. Mine took 1 hour 40 minutes to double in size.

Assembly
1 – Take the topping mix and divide it into 6 equal pieces
2 – Using baking paper (or a tortilla press if you have one) and a flat bottom plate or pan, press them so they are just larger than the buns. This stage can also be done in advance and chilled.
3 – Take the topping disc and lay it over each of the buns
4 – Using a knive, score or press the pattern of a pineapple criss cross into the sugary topping
5 – Preheat the oven to 180c
6 – Glaze each of the buns with some egg wash, an egg beaten with two tablespoons of water
7 – Bake the buns for 20-25 minutes
8 – Leave to cool and serve with a slab of cold butter wedged inside #symmetrybreakfast

node.text: Buongiorno Bologna! 🇮🇹 A few days in and the jet lag has finally subsided and I’ve landed in our new home. A very modest 16th century palazzo and former home of Pope Benedict XIV. Whilst we wait for the arrival of literally everthing from Shanghai and London, we don’t even have a chair to sit on, so breakfast on the floor it is! Girelle al rosmarino, mortadella, culatello, pecorino from Sardinia (one of my faves) hard boiled eggs done in an electric kettle, a little muesli and a cup of Earl Grey. Living the Continental breakfast dream on the continent! Soon I’ll be out and about and sampling the delights of one of the world’s most famous cities for food, Bologna! 🥰 #symmetrybreakfast

node.text: My penultimate day in Shanghai, room service breakfast at @themiddlehouse where I’ve been staying the past few days is the most perfect send off. I’ve said it before but what a wonderful four and a half years it has been living in Shanghai and exploring China, Asia and the other side of the world. Tomorrow evening I’ll (touch wood!) fly off to Italy. Excited, sick to my stomach, butterflies, elation, loss and joy. So much to look forward to and so many things I’ll miss, but no regrets at all! Love to you all! ❤️❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
Chai & brown sugar Hop Tarts! 🦗Seemingly like any regular breakfast toaster pie but with a twist. For my next #friendswithbreakfast I’ve got my friend Joy @getbuggie who is the Shanghai Queen of all things entomophagy. Incorporating cricket powder into the dough and a filling using a cricket chai spice powder from @orchestraprovisions Joy has created a breakfast that is not only delicious but packed with sustainable protein, fibre and all 9 essential amino acids. I have to say I’m a total convert. The tarts are then topped with dried ants, that taste of intense citrus that are excellent with the chai flavour 
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
Having Joy in my kitchen today was quite the learning curve, to find out so much about the potential of insects, their nutritional prowess using less land and water to produce than almost all crops but also beating meat for nutritional density whilst also tasting pretty damn good. A few months ago I asked in Stories what foods made you uncomfortable and many said insects but really I don’t see the fuss. Follow Joy for some great ideas and recipes #entomophagy #insectprotein #sustainablefood #symmetrybreakfast

Eggs 🍳🍳 with a little creation of my own, a Chinese garlic chive pesto 韭菜派斯托 (made with jiucai, white furu 白豆腐乳, macadamia nuts and sesame oil. Fresh, almost spicy raw garlic hit with the salty rich 鲜味 umami flavour bomb of furu. Paired ever so amazingly with a breakfast cookie from @strictlycookies, the very limited Cinnamon Breakfast Crunch cookie snickerdoodle of dreams!!
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
Introducing my next #friendswithbreakfast, the GAWJUS Lexie, the creator of Strictly Cookies, since 2010 she has cemented her position as the Cookie Queen of China 👸🏼 She has created literally hundreds of flavours over the last 10 years, from classic chocolate chip, to Yangmei & Coconut, Purple Potato & white chocolate, Spicy Mexican Hot Chocolate, a Jianbing cookie! and my personal all time favourite the Snack Pack. You can find her cookies in hundreds of cafes and restaurants across the Middle Kingdom. Say 👋🏼 if you’re a fan ❤️ #symmetrybreakfast

node.text:
Breakfast in Ningxia, unfortunately couldn’t find much of a local breakfast scene in Yinchuan, the provincial capital of China’s most recognised wine region, so settled for a local Henan restaurant serving hú là tāng胡辣汤 a spiced beef and pepper (as in peppercorn not chilli pepper) soup. Whilst 胡辣 means peppercorns, the hú 胡 character can also mean a beard 🧔🏻, but also symbolic of anything foreign or barbaric so I’ve always called this Spicy Beard Soup myself. Mandarin is very good at giving us fingerprints of history, especially in the names of foods that are non native like 西红柿 tomato (literally western red persimmon) or 西瓜 🍉 watermelon (western melon). The soup is a thick and incredibly filling meal heavy on the pepper, chilli, anise, ginger and probably a lot more than I can identify. With some youtiao and a baozi on the side.
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
I’ve been in Ningxia this weekend to learn more about one of China’s wine growing regions. They only started growing here in the early 1980s, fascinating to see what will happen here in the future #symmetrybreakfast

node.text:
Syrniki and strawberry varenye, a classic Russian dish. #Syrniki is a type of curd cheese dumpling/pancake that is slightly tangy, sweet, light and extremely moreish. Served with homemade varenye, a whole fruit jam. Today I’m joined by @drawmedenis my brother from a Russian mother. Mark and I arrived in Shanghai the same week as Denis and have been friends from the start. His illustrations reference classical compositions and combine them with modernist colour palettes. A visual hodgepodge that combines hedonism and nihilism co-existing in contemporary queer culture and reflects on his own upbringing in a traditional Russian Orthodox family. 
- - - - - - - - - - - -
Since Mark is now in Italy and it will be another few months before I join him with the cat, I’ve decided to have some of my best friends over for breakfast. #friendswithbreakfast #fwb is my way of sharing with you some people in Shanghai I admire the most. #symmetrybreakfast

手抓饼 Shou Zhua Bing, aka Hand Grab Pancake, you’ll find them in street stands around China but they’re definitely more common in Taiwan. It’s that wonderful intersection where snack, lunch, drunk food, hangover food and breakfast converge. A simple shop bought frozen scallion pancake 葱油饼 with egg, bacon, a cheese single, some Sichuan style 土豆丝 shredded potato, chilli crisp, white pepper, 甜面酱 tianmianjiang and mayo 😍😝
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
I gave it a hot second of thought about how I would post two breakfasts now that we are in the process of leaving Shanghai and Mark is already settling into Bologna. I’m still here for 3 months in an empty house waiting for paperwork for our cat. But then I thought, well I make the rules here and I’ll just eat two or have friends over. Who’s going to volunteer?! 😂  #symmetrybreakfast

node.text: Almost every week, I open my inbox and find myself reading a message of unbelievable racist hatred directed at me because I live in China. I have a close circle of friends that we discuss these things but rarely does it go any further. I cannot even begin to imagine what some of my friends and followers must experience on a daily basis. Just fucking unbelievable sometimes the shit that it thrown around and the way the media behaves. People who attack elderly Asian people are cowards. What’s shocking about the recent events in Atlanta is that it most certainly will happen again. At least now people are starting to recognise that racism against the East and South East Asian community exists and can start to tackle the issue. It’s about time #stopasianhate

node.text:
HOT CROSS BUNS

Ingredients

350g strong flour (plus 50g to make paste cross)
170ml milk
2 tbsp marmalade
50g butter
50g sugar
7g dried yeast
Big pinch of salt
1 tsp ground cinnamon
2 eggs
70g raisins or chopped dates
Zest of whole lemon
Zest of whole orange
2 tbsp golden syrup

Method

1. Heat milk, butter and marmalade until the butter has melted, cool
2. Combine flour, sugar, yeast, salt, cinnamon in a bowl
3. Add the cooled milk, marmalade and butter mix, add one whole egg. Combine to form a wet but not too sticky dough, knead for 5 minutes and leave to rise for an hour
4. Beat the dough back, add the raisins, orange and lemon zest and knead again. Leave to rest for another hour
5. Divide the dough into 8 equal sizes (best to weigh) and shape them into balls. Line a baking tray and cover to rise for another hour!
6. Preheat the oven to 200c
7. Brush the buns with an egg glaze
8. Mix the remaining flour with enough water to make a thick paste. Use a piping bag (for sandwich bag with the corner snipped off) Make a cross over each bun
9. Bake for 20 minutes
10. Heat the Golden Syrup until loose and warm, brush over the buns as soon as they come out of the oven
11. Leave to cool, slice them open, toast and serve with liberal amounts of butter
